Datasets uploaded through the Uploads API are a different kind of dataset from the dataset resources of the (beta) Dataset API and there is no API method to delete them.

Our testing strategy for the upload API: keep a manageable number of semi-permanent datasets around, one per test suite, and reuse them. The name of the destination datasets will be provided by a `uploads_dest_id` fixture in the project `conftest.py`.

```python
@pytest.fixture
def uploads_dest_id():
    version = os.environ.get('TRAVIS_PYTHON_VERSION', 'test')
    return 'uploads-{0}'.format(version.replace(".", "-"))
```

Consider this example:

```python
from klein import route, run
from twisted.web.template import Element, renderer, TagLoader, tags
from twisted.internet.task import deferLater
from twisted.internet import reactor


class AnElement(Element):
    loader = TagLoader(tags.html(tags.body(tags.h1("OK GO"),
                                           tags.div(render="slow"))))

    @renderer
    def slow(self, request, tag):
        return deferLater(reactor, 1.0, lambda: u"okay, later")


@route("/")
def something(request):
    return AnElement()

run("localhost", 8210)
```

One would expect a web page that says "okay, later", but instead we just get one that says "OK GO" and then horrible tracebacks.

When an index which belongs to a field returned by the call to `portal_atct` ([`tool.getEnabledFields()`](https://github.com/eea/eea.facetednavigation/blob/master/eea/facetednavigation/widgets/sorting/widget.py#L112)) is not actually present in the `portal_catalog`, the [`criteriaByIndexId`](https://github.com/eea/eea.facetednavigation/blob/master/eea/facetednavigation/widgets/sorting/widget.py#L93) method breaks on attempting to retrieve the index object from `portal_catalog`.

Such a circumstance can arise, for example, if you install `alm.solrindex` which by default deletes text indexes such as `Title` and `Description` and gives over indexing those fields to solr.  The line of code linked above throws a key error which then prevents the widget from rendering at all.

One possible fix is to wrap the lookup in a try...except clause like so:

```python
    def criteriaByIndexId(self, indexId):
        catalog_tool = getToolByName(self.context, 'portal_catalog')
        try:
            indexObj = catalog_tool.Indexes[indexId]
        except KeyError:
            return ()
        #...
```

